    "markdown": "---\ntitle: \"Benchmarking Fixed Effects Implementations and Solvers\"\ndescription: \"Runtime comparison of PyFixest, fixest, FixedEffectModels.jl, and Correia's published Stata results on real-world HDFE datasets.\"\ncategories: [performance, fixed effects, benchmarks]\njupyter: python3\nformat:\n  html:\n    html-table-processing: none\ntoc: true\ntoc-title: \"On this page\"\ntoc-location: left\n---\n\n## Overview\n\n[Sergio Correia's HDFE benchmark suite](https://www.scorreia.com/data/hdfe/index.html)\nconsists of a collection of real-world datasets that stress different graph topologies and are the most extensive collection of public benchmark data sets for HDFE solvers we are aware of.\n\nIn addition, we also include benchmarks on synthetic data generating processes from the\n[fixest benchmarks](https://github.com/kylebutts/fixest_benchmarks) suite, which have formed a core reference point for PyFixest development and contrast nicely the relative strenghts and weaknesses of different solvers.\n\nWe benchmark solvers in PyFixest against the following references:\n\n- [**fixest**](https://lrberge.github.io/fixest/), which is the reference HDFE implementation in R. `fixest` implements a MAP-style solver with Irons-Tuck acceleration and other optimizations.\n- [**FixedEffectModels.jl**](https://github.com/FixedEffects/FixedEffectModels.jl), which is the reference Julia implementation and implements an LSMR solver with diagonal preconditioning\n- [**reghdfe**](https://scorreia.com/software/reghdfe/) via [**Sergio Correia's published Stata results**](https://www.scorreia.com/data/hdfe/index.html), which is the reference Stata implementation that includes a wide variety of solvers.\n\nAll Python, Julia and R benchmarks are run on Alex' local machine (Mac mini, Apple M4, 10 cores, 16 GB RAM, macOS 15.3.1); because Alex does not have access to Stata, we take the Stata runtimes from Sergio Correia's website. This leads to the caveat that Stata runtimes are not directly comparable to the other benchmarks due to hardware differences.\n\nFor the Correia data sets, we fit two-way fixed effects regressions using the `fixest`, `PyFixest` and `FixedEffectModels.jl` defaults: this means that all packages drop multicollinear variables (albeit using different algorithms), drop singletions, and use iid inference. To get closer to the Stata benchmarks, we change the default tolerance to `1e-8` for the Stata benchmarks. Note that convergence criteria differ across implementations, so the tolerance is only a common stopping threshold and does not guarantee identical convergence behavior across packages.\nFor the `fixest` benchmark, we use the default 1e-6 tolerance for `fixest`, `PyFixest` and `FixedEffectModels.jl` and fit three-way fixed effects models using the \"simple\" and \"difficult\" DGPs.\n\n::: {.callout}\nFor an explanation why different fixed effects / graph structures lead to differences in solver performance, please take a look at the [When Are Fixed Effects Estimations Difficult?](difficult-fixed-effects.md) vignette.\n:::\n\n\n## Benchmarks\n\n::: {#9d5a82c3 .cell execution_count=1}\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=1}\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"pkydxexkwz\" style=\"padding-left:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;overflow-x:auto;overflow-y:auto;width:auto;height:auto;\">\n<style>\n#pkydxexkwz table {\n          font-family: -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Oxygen, Ubuntu, Cantarell, 'Helvetica Neue', 'Fira Sans', 'Droid Sans', Arial, sans-serif;\n          -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;\n          -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale;\n        }\n\n#pkydxexkwz thead, tbody, tfoot, tr, td, th { border-style: none; }\n tr { background-color: transparent; }\n#pkydxexkwz p { margin: 0; padding: 0; }\n #pkydxexkwz .gt_table { display: table; border-collapse: collapse; line-height: normal; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; color: #333333; font